definitions.definition: a group of insects which comprises the damselflies.
the thick-walled resting cell of certain fungi and algae, arising from the fusion of two similar gametes.
the second stage of the prophase of meiosis, following leptotene, during which homologous chromosomes begin to pair.

origin: late 19th century: from Greek zugōtos ‘yoked’, from zugoun ‘to yoke’.

definitions.definition: a diploid cell resulting from the fusion of two haploid gametes; a fertilized ovum.

origin: 1930s: from German, of unknown origin.

definitions.definition: hydrogen cyanide adsorbed on or released from a carrier in the form of small tablets, used as an insecticidal fumigant and by the Nazis as a lethal gas.

origin: late 19th century: from French, from Greek zumē ‘leaven’.

definitions.definition: a mixture of enzymes obtained from yeast which catalyse the breakdown of sugars in alcoholic fermentation.
an inactive substance which is converted into an enzyme when activated by another enzyme.

origin: from Greek zumē ‘leaven’.

definitions.definition: relating to enzymes or fermentation.
definitions.example: zymogen

definitions.definition: relating to or denoting contagious disease regarded as developing after infection, by a process analogous to fermentation.

origin: mid 19th century: from Greek zumē ‘leaven’, on the pattern of metallurgy.

definitions.definition: the study or practice of fermentation in brewing, winemaking, or distilling.
former term for Komi2 (the language).
